        }
      }
    ],
    "reasoning": "The Firestore structure is designed to ensure security, scalability, and ease of debugging, following the principles of Authorization Independence, Clarity of Intent, DBAC (Database-Based Access Control), and QAPs (Rules are not Filters). Authorization Independence is achieved through denormalization, where necessary, copying relevant authorization data to subcollections to avoid `get()` calls in security rules. Structural Segregation ensures that each collection has a homogeneous security posture. Access Modeling standardizes authorization patterns. The structure uses path-based ownership for private user data and membership maps for collaborative data.\n\nSpecifically, to address the 'list' permission error on the 'testimonials' path, all paths are designed to enable secure `list` operations by segregating data based on access requirements and utilizing membership maps where applicable. The Feedback collection includes an `approved` field to control which testimonials are displayed publicly.  Admin users are managed via a dedicated collection `/roles_admin/{uid}` to manage admin privileges.\n\nQAPs are supported through structural segregation. Publicly accessible data, like approved testimonials, reside in `/feedback` with the `approved` flag and can be listed securely. Admin-controlled data, like services and projects, can be listed with appropriate authorization checks on `/roles_admin/{uid}`."
